\par I really ought to start again, though. Begin afresh. Leave Sabon to her admirers for now. There will be time to return to her later.
\par \tab {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} often started over\emdash he loved nothing better than to start again in the middle of a book, like a magician appearing to disappear
\emdash to leave the reader hanging precariously over an abyss while building up some other story line, only to bring it all back together seamlessly in the end, averting disaster. I would be a fool to promise to duplicate such a feat.
\par \tab For a time, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} sat next to the desk in my apartment\emdash in an old comfortable yellow chair our parents had bought in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Stockton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} many years before. There he would sit, illumined by a single lamp in a twilight broken only by calls to prayer from the Religious Quarte
r, and chuckle as he read over the transcript of his latest chapter. He loved his own jokes as if they were his children, worthy of affection no matter how slack-jawed, limb}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
