\par \tab He had become a big man by then, with a graying beard, prone to wearing a gray jacket or overcoat that hid his ever-evolving physical peculiarities. Sometimes he would indulge in a cigar\emdash 
a habit newly-acquired from his association with the fringe historian James Lacond\emdash and sit back in his chair and smok
e, and I would find him there, gazing off into a memory I might or might not be able to share. His troubles, his disease, could not touch him in those moments.
\par \tab I much prefer to remember my brother in that space, calm and very much at the center of himself
. While he was there, many regular tavern-goers referred to him as the God of the Green Light, looking as he did both timeless and timeworn. Now that he is gone, I imagine he has become the Ghost of the Green Light, and will enter the annals of the Spore 
as a quiet, luminescent legend. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} would have liked that idea: }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 let it be so.
