\par \tab If there is a starting point in Duncan\rquote s life, it would have to be the day that our father, Jonathan Shriek, a 
minor historian, died of convulsive joy at our house in Stockton, a town some hundred miles south of Ambergris, on the other side of the River Moth. This joy ripped through our father and destroyed his heart when I was thirteen and Duncan only ten. I reme
mber because I was seated at the kitchen table doing my homework when the mailman came to the door. Father heard the bell and hopped up to answer it. Father was a defiantly ugly man, built like a toad, with wattles and stocky legs. 
\par \tab I heard him in the hall
, talking about the weather with the mailman. The door shut. The crinkle of paper as my father opened the envelope. A moment of silence, as of breath being sucked in. Then a horribly huge laugh, a cry of joy or triumph, or both. He came into the kitchen, 
and barreled past me to the open hallway that led to the back door.
\par \tab \'93Gale,\'94 he was shouting. \'93Gale,\'94 my mother\rquote s name. Out into the backyard he stumbled, me right behind him, my homework forgotten, beside myself with suspense. Something marvelous had happened and I wanted to know what it was.

\par \tab At the far end of the lawn, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, ten and still sandy-haired, was helping our mother with the small herb garden. My father ran toward them, into the heart of the summer day. The trees were lazy in the breeze. Bees c
lustered around yellow flowers. He was waving the letter over his head and yelling, \'93Gale! {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}! Gale! {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}!\'94 His back to me. Me running after him, asking, \'93What, Dad? What is it?\'94}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid8128033\charrsid6828570 
 (I remember this with the same kind of focused intensity as you, Janice. Dad was running toward us. I was smiling because I loved }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid8916811\charrsid6828570 seeing }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid8128033\charrsid6828570 Dad\rquote s enthusiasm. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid8916811\charrsid6828570 I loved seeing him so euphoric, so unselfconscious for once.)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
