\par \tab I called out, \'93Who is it?\'94 and received, in such a jubilant tone that I could not at first place the voice, the response, \'93Your brother, Duncan!\'94
 Shocked, relieved, perplexed, I opened the door to a pale, worn, yet strangely bulky brother wrapped in an old gray overcoat that he held closed with both hands. Comically enough, a sailor\rquote 
s hat covered his head. His face was flushed, his eyes too bright as he staggered past me, pieces of debris falling from him onto the floor of my living room.
\par \tab I locked the door behind him and turned to 
greet him, but any words I might have spoken died in my throat. For he held his overcoat open like the wings of some great bird, and what I saw I could not at first believe. Just brightly-colored vest and pants, I thought, but protruding, like barnacles o
n a ship\rquote s hull. How unlike my brother to wear anything that outlandish. I took a step closer\'85
\par \tab \'93That\rquote s right,\'94 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} said, \'93step closer and really }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 see}{
