\par \tab He tossed his hat onto a chair. He had shaved off his hair, and his scalp was stippled and layered in a hundred shades of blue, yellow, green, orange.
\par \tab \'93Mushrooms. Hundreds of mushrooms. I had to wear the overcoat and hat or every casual tourist on {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Albumuth Boulevard{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} would have stared at me.
\'94 He looked down at his body. \'93Look how they glow. What a shame to be rid of them.\'94 He saw me staring unabashedly. \'93Stare all you like, Janice. I\rquote m a dazzling butterfly, not a moth\'85well, for another hour or two.\'94
 (A butterfly could not compare. I was magnificent. Every part of my body was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 receiving}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 . I could \'93hear\'94 thing
s through my body, feel them, that no human short of Samuel Tonsure could understand.)
\par \tab He did not lie. From the collar of his shirt to the tips of his shoes, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
