\par \tab He took off his overcoat, let it fall to the floor. \'93I agree\emdash I look ridiculous.\'94
\par \tab \'93But where have you been? How did this happen?\'94 I asked.
\par \tab He put a finger to his lips. \'93I\rquote ll answer your questions if you\rquote ll help me get rid of this second skin. It itches. And it\rquote s dying.\'94
\par 
\par So I helped him. It was not as simple as having him step out of his clothes, because the mushrooms had eaten through his clothes and attached themselves to his poor pale skin. A madness of mushrooms, mottling his skin\emdash 
no uniform shape or variety or size. Some pulsed a strobing pink-blue. Others radiated a dull, deep burgundy. A few hung from his waist like upside-down wine glasses, translucent and hollow, the space inside filled with clusters of t
iny button-shaped green-gold nodules that disintegrated at the slightest touch. Textures from rough to smooth to rippled to grainy to slick. Smells\emdash 
the smells all ran together into an earthy but not unpleasant tang, punctuated by a hint of mint. The mushrooms even made noises if you listened carefully enough\emdash a soft }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 pough }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 as they released spores, an intermittent whine when left alone, a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 pop}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570  as they became ghosts through my rough relocations.
\par \tab \'93Remember BDD when you three had to wash all that mud and filth off of me?\'94 he asked, as we both worked with scrubbing implements and towels in the bathroom.
\par \tab \'93Of course I do,\'94 I said.
\par \tab Before Dad Died, BDD, a grim little acronym meant to help us remember when we had been a happy family. If we had arguments or bouts of d
epression that threatened to get out of control, one of us would remind the others that we had all behaved differently before Dad died. We held BDD time in our heads as a sanctuary whenever our anger, our loss, became too great.
\par \tab Once, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, his usual mad, exploring BDD}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
