 found that his editor was \'93on vacation\'94 and that F&L's president, Mr. L. Gaudy, would talk to him instead.
\par \tab A secretary quickly escorted {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} into Gaudy's office, and left immediately. (I remember the office quite well. It was \'93resplendent,\'94
 with a rosewood desk, a dozen portraits of famous F&L authors, and an angry, spitting fireplace in the corner opposite the desk.)
\par \tab Gaudy, according to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}'s journal, was \'93a bearded man of indeterminate age, his gaunt flesh wrapped across sharp cheekbones.\'94
 He sat behind his desk, staring at the room's fireplace. (His eyes were like blue ice, and in his presence I smelled a certain cloying mustiness, as if he spent most of his time underground, or surrounded by hundred-year-old books.)
\par \tab {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} moved to sit, but Gaudy raised one hand, palm out, in abeyance. The calm behind the gesture, almost trance-like, made }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
