\par 
\par This time, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} had a haunted look about him, the j
oy of his previous underground adventures stripped away, leaving behind only a gauntness akin to death. The paleness that had taken over his features had blanched away any expression, any life, in his limbs, in his movements. He:
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 \tab Beard like the tendrils of finely-threaded spores.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 \tab Swayed in the doorway like a tall, ensanguinated ghost, holding the door open with one shaking, febrile arm.
\par \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 Shoes tattered and torn, as if savaged by a dog.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 \tab Muttered my name as if in the middle of a dream.
\par \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 Clothes stained everywhere with spores, reduced to a fine, metallic dust that glittered blackly all around him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 \tab Trailed tiny obsidian mushrooms, trembling off of him at every turn.
\par \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 Eyes embedded with black flecks, staring at some nameless vision just beyond me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 \tab Clutched something tightly in his left hand, knuckles pale against the dark coating of spore dust.
\par 
\par He staggered inside, fell to the floor amid the paintings, the curled canvases, the naked frames vainglorious with the vision of the wall behind them. The gallery did smell of turpentine, of freshly-cut wood, of drying paint. But as 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} met the floor, or the floor met {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, the smells became one smell: the smell of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. A dark green smell brought from deep underground. A subtle interweaving of minerals and fles
h and fungus. The smell of old water trickling through stones and earth. The smell of lichen and moss. (Flesh penetrated by fungus, you mean\emdash 
every pore cross-pollinated, supersaturated. Nothing very subtle about it. The flesh alive and prickly.) The smell, now, of my brother.
\par \tab I locked the door behind him. I slapped his face until his gaze cleared, and he saw me. With my help, he got to his feet and I took him into the back room. He was so light. He might as well have been a skeleton draped with canvas. I b
egan to cry. His ribs bent against my encircling arm as I gently laid him down against a wall. His clothes were so filthy that I made him take them off and put on a painter\rquote s smock.
\par \tab I forced bread and cheese on him. He didn\rquote t want it at first. I had to tear the bread into small pieces and hold his mouth open. I had to make him close his mouth. \'93Swallow.\'94 He had no choice. He couldn\rquote t fight me\emdash 
he was too weak. Or I was, for once, too strong.
\par \tab Eventually, he took the bread from my hands, began to eat on his own. Still he said nothing, just stared at me with eyes white against the dust-stippled darkness of his forehead and jutting cheekbones.
\par \tab \'93When you are ready, speak,\'94 I said. \'93You are not leaving here until you tell me exactly what happened. You are not leaving here until I know why. Why, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}? What happened to you?\'94 I couldn\rquote t keep the anguish from my voice.
\par \tab {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} smiled up at me. A drunkard\rquote s smile. A skeleton\rquote s smile. My brother\rquote s smile, as laconic as ever. 
\par \tab \'93Same old sister,\'94 he said. \'93I knew I could count on you. To half kill me trying to feed me.\'94 (To help me. Who else would help me back then?)
\par \tab \'93I mean it. I won\rquote t let you leave without telling me what happened.\'94
\par \tab He smiled again, but he wouldn\rquote t look at me. For a long time, he said nothing as I watched him.
\par \tab Then the flood. He spoke and spoke and spoke\emdash rambling, fragmented, coherent, clever. I began to grow afraid for him. All these words. There was already less than nothing inside of him. I could see that. When the last words had left his mouth, 
would even the canvas of his skin flap away free, the filigree of his bones disintegrate into dust? Slowly, I managed to hear the words and forget the condition of the one who spoke them. Forget that he was my brother.
\par \tab He had gone deeper into the underground this time, but the research had gone badly. He kept interspersing his account with mutterings that he would \'93never do it again.\'94 And, \'93If I stay on the surface, I\rquote m safe. I should be safe.\'94
 At the time, I thought he meant staying physically above ground, but now I\rquote m not so sure. (}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid4986387\charrsid6828570 Be sure.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 
) I wonder if he also meant the surface of his }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid4986387\charrsid6828570 mind}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 
 That if he could simply restrain himself from the divergent thinking, the untoward analysis, that had marked some of his previous books, he might once again be a published writer. (}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid4986387\charrsid6828570 
Who knows? I might have given up on myself if forced to listen to my own ravings. I might have even become a respectable citizen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 .)
\par \tab As he spoke, I realized I wasn\rquote t ready for his revelations. I had made a mistake\emdash I didn\rquote t want to hear what he
 had to say. I needed distance from this shivering, shuddering wreck of a man. He clutched to the edges of the smock I had given him like a corpse curling fingers around a coffin\rquote 
s lining. Somehow, the look on his face made me think of our father dying in the summer grass. It frightened me. I tried to put boundaries on the conversation.
\par \tab "What happened to the book you were working on?" I asked him.
\par \tab He grimaced, but the expression made him look more human, and his gaze turned inward, the horrors reflected there no longer trying to get out.
\par \tab "Still-born," he gasped, as if just breaking to the surface after being held down in black water. He lurched to his feet, fell back down again. Every surface he touched became covered in fine black powder. \'93Still-born,\'94 he repeated. \'93
Or I killed it. I don\rquote t know which. Maybe I\rquote m a murderer. I was.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid4790165\charrsid6828570 ..}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 
 I was half-way through. On fire with ancient texts. Bloated with the knowledge in them. Didn\rquote t think I needed firsthand }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid4790165\charrsid6828570 experience }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 to write the book. Such a web of words, Janice. I have never used so many words. I used so many there weren\rquote t any left to write with. And yet, I still had this fear deep in my skull. I couldn\rquote t get it out.
\'94}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid4329825\charrsid6828570  (I still can\rquote t get it out of my head, sometimes. {\*\atrfstart 108106809}It\rquote s like writing a book}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs24\v\insrsid12132411\charrsid6828570 
