\cs24\fs16\insrsid9317075 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9317075 I find this simile a little odd\emdash or redundant, maybe?\emdash given that it *is* writing a book that he\rquote s attempting to find a comparison to.}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid4329825\charrsid6828570 \emdash that fear of the unknown never really goes away. After awhile, it becomes a comfort.)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 
\par \tab He relinquished his grasp on the object in his hand, which I had almost forgotten.
\par \tab It rolled across the floor. We both stared at it, he as astonished as I. A honey-and-parchment-colored ball. Of flesh? Of tissue? Of stone?
\par \tab He looked up at me. \'93I remember now. It needs moisture. If it dries, it dies. Cracks form in its skin. It\rquote s curled into a ball to preserve a pearl of moisture between its cilia.\'94
\par \tab \'93What is it?\'94 I said, unable to keep the fear from my voice.
\par \tab He grinned in recognition of my tone. \'93Before Dad died,\'94 he said, \'93you would have found this creature a wonderful mystery. You would have followed me out into the woods and we would have dug up fire-red salamanders just to see their 
eyes glow in the dark.\'94
\par \tab \'93No,\'94 I said. \'93No. There was no time when I would have found this }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 thing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 
 a wonderful mystery. Where did you find it?\'94
\par \tab His smirk, the way it ate up his face, the way it accentuated the suddenly taut bones in his neck, made the flesh around his mouth a vassal to his mirth, sickened me.
\par \tab \'93Where do }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 you}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570  think it came from?\'94
\par \tab I ignored the question, turned away, said, \'93I have a canteen of water in the front, near my desk. But keep talking. Keep telling me about your book.\'94
\par \tab He frowned as I walked past him into the main room of the gallery. From behind me, his disembodied voice rose up, quavered, continued. A thrush caught in a hunter\rquote 
s snare, flapping this way and that, ever more entangled and near its death. His smell had coated the entir
e gallery. In a sense, I was as close to him searching for the canteen as if I stood beside him. Beyond the gallery windows lay the real world, composed of unnaturally bright colors and shoppers walking briskly by.
\par \tab \'93So I never finished it, Janice. What do you think of that? I couldn\rquote t. Wouldn\rquote t. I wrote and wrote. I wrote with the energy of ten men}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid3953289\charrsid6828570  each}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570  evening. All texts I consulted interlocked under my dexterous manipulations. It all made such perfect sense\'85and then I began to panic. Each word, I realize
d, had been leading me farther and farther away from the central mystery. Every sentence left a false trail. Every paragraph formed another wall between me and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid3953289\charrsid6828570 my thesis}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 . Soon, I stopped writing. It had all been going so well. How could it get so bad so quickly?
\par \tab \'93I soon found out. I backtracked through the abyss of words, searching for a flaw, a fissure, a crack in the foundation. Perhaps some paragraph had turned traitor and would reveal itself. Only it wasn\rquote 
t a paragraph. It was a single word, five pages from the end of my silly scribblings, in a sentence of no particular importance. Just a single word. I know the sentence by heart, because I\rquote ve repeated it to myself over and over again. It\rquote 
s all that\rquote s left of my book. Do you want to hear it?\'94
\par \tab \'93Yes,\'94 I said, still looking for the canteen under all the canvases, although I wasn\rquote t sure.
\par \tab \'93Here it is: \lquote But surely, if Tonsure had not known the truth then, he knew it after traveling underground.\rquote  The word, of course, was \lquote truth,\rquote  and I could not get past the 
truth. The truth stank of the underground, buried under dead leaves and hidden in cold, dry, dark caverns. The truth had }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid14236719\charrsid6828570 little }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 to do with the surface of things.
\par \tab \'93From that word, in that context, on that page, written in my nearly-illegible hand, my master work, my beautiful, marvelous book unraveled syllable by syllable. I began by just crossing out words that did not belong in the sentence. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid3953289\charrsid6828570 Then}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570  I began to delete words by rules as illegitimate and illogical as the gray caps themselves. Until after a week
, I woke up one morning, determined to continue my surgical editing of the manuscript\emdash only to find that not even the original sentence had been spared: all that remained of my once-proud manuscript was that single word: \lquote truth\rquote 
. And, truth, my dear sister, was not a big enough word to constitute an entire book\emdash at least not to me.\'94 (Or my publishers, come to think of it. If there had been any publishers.)
\par \tab I had found the canteen. I came back into the room and handed it to him. \'93You should drink some. Rinse out the lie you\rquote ve just told.\'94
\par \tab He snorted, took the canteen, raised it to his lips, and, drinking from it, kissed it as seriously as he would a lover.
\par \tab \'93Perhaps it is in part a metaphor,\'94 he said, \'93but it is still, ironically enough, the truth.\'94
\par \tab \'93Don\rquote t speak in metaphors, then. How do you tell truth from lies otherwise?\'94
\par \tab \'93I want to be taken literally.\'94
\par \tab \'93You mean literarily, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Except you\rquote ve already been taken literarily\emdash they\rquote 
ve all ravished you and gone on to the next victim.\'94
\par \tab \'93Literally.\'94
\par \tab \'93Is that why you brought this horrible rolled up ball of an animal with you? Metaphor become flesh?\'94
\par \tab \'93No. I forgot I had it. Now that I\rquote ve brought it here, I can\rquote t let it die.\'94 (Actually, Janice, I did bring it with me on purpose. I had just forgotten the purpose.)
\par \tab He sidled up to the golden ball of flesh, poured water into his hand.
\par \tab He looked up at me, the expression on his face taking me back to all of his foolish explorations as a child. \'93Watch now! Watch carefully!\'94
\par \tab Slowly, he poured water over the golden ball. After a moment the gold color blushed into a haze of purple-yellow-blue-green, which then returned to gold, but a more vibrant shade of gold that flashed in the dim light. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} poured more water over the creature. It seemed to crack apart, fissures erupting across its skin at regular intervals. But no\emdash 
it was merely opening up, each of its four legs unfurling from the top of the ball, to settle upside down on the floor. Immediately, it leapt up, spun, and landed, cilia down, revealed as a kind of phosphorescent starfish.
\par \tab {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} dribbled still more water over it. Each of its four arms shone a different glittering shade\emdash green-blue-yellow-purple\emdash 
the edges of the blue arm tinged green on one side, yellow on the other.
\par \tab \'93A starfish,\'94 I said.
\par \tab \'93A compass,\'94 he said. \'93Just one of the many wonders to be found below ground. A living compass. North is blue, so if you turn it like so,\'94 and he reached over and carefully turned the starfish, \'93
the arm shines perfectly blue, facing as it does due north.\'94 
\par \tab Indeed, the blue had been cleansed of any green or yellow taint.
\par \tab \'93This compass saved me more than once when I was lost,\'94 he said.
\par \tab I stared at my ungainly, stacked frames. \'93I\rquote m sick of wonders, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. This is just a color to me, just a trick. The true wonder is t
hat you\rquote re still alive. No one could have expected that. You suffer what may have been a mental breakdown, go down below, return with a living compass, and expect me to say\'85what? How }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 wonderful}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570  that is? How }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 awed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570  I am by it all? No. I\rquote m appalled. I\rquote m horrified. I\rquote m angry. I\rquote ve failed at one career after another. I\rquote m about to open my own gallery. I haven\rquote 
t seen you in almost ten years, and you shamble in here, a talking skeleton\emdash and you expect me to be impressed by a magic show? Have you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 seen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570  yourself lately?\'94
\par \tab I can\rquote t remember ever being so furious\emdash and out of nowhere, out of almost nothing. My hands shook. My shoulders had become rigid blocks of stone. My throat ached. And I\rquote 
m not even sure why. (Because you were scared, and because you were my sister, and you loved me. Even when you were mad at me, I was your family.)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid14236719\charrsid6828570  {\*\atrfstart 108113409}
