\chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9317075 Whoops\'85 is there a line of dialogue missing here? Janice asking \'93Who?,\'94 perhaps?}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 \tab \'93Free of what?\'94
\par \tab Pale hands, darkened face, gray speech. \'93I think they care nothing for us one way or the other, Janice. They have only one purpose now. The same purpose they\rquote ve had for centuries.\'94
\par \tab \'93In your unconfirmed opinion, brother,\'94 I said, and shivered at the way the mushroom dust on his face still glittered darkly.
\par \tab \'93What did they teach you about the Silence at university?\'94
\par \tab \'93The gray caps killed everyone in the city,\'94 I said.
\par \tab He shook his head. Forgetting the starfish in his hands, he stood abruptly. The starfish fell to the floor and began to curl and uncurl in a reflexive imitation of pain. Now {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}
}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} was stooped over
 me. Now he was crouched beside me. If there were ever a secret he truly wanted to tell me, this was the secret. This was the cause of it. We had returned to the last survivor of his sixth book, alive amid all of the suicides: the truth. As my brother saw
 it.
\par \tab \'93You learned it wrong,\'94 he told me. \'93That\rquote s not what happened. It didn\rquote t happen like that. I\rquote ve seen so many things, and I\rquote ve thought a lot about what I\rquote 
ve seen. They disappeared without a single drop of blood left behind. Not a fragment of bone. No. They weren\rquote 
t killed. At least not directly. Try to imagine a different answer: a sudden miscalculation, a botched experiment, a flaw in the machine. All of those people. All twenty-five thousand of them. The men, the women, the children\emdash they didn\rquote 
t die. They were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 moved}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 . The door opened in a way the gray caps didn\rquote t expect, couldn\rquote 
t expect, and all those people\emdash they were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 moved}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 
 by mistake. The machine took them to some place else. And, yes, maybe they died, and maybe they died horribly\emdash but my point is, it was all an }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 accident}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 . A mistake. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 A terrible, pointless blunder}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 .\'94
\par \tab He was breathing heavily. Sweat glistened on his arms, where before the black dust had suppressed it.
\par \tab \'93That\rquote s crazy,\'94 I said. \'93That\rquote s the craziest thing I have ever heard in my life. They\rquote ve killed thousands of people. They\rquote ve done terrible things. And you have the nerve to make apologies for them?!\'94
\par \tab \'93Would it be easier to accept that they don\rquote t give a damn about us one way or the other if we hadn\rquote t massacred them to build this city? What I thi
nk is crazy is that we try to pretend they are just like us. If we had massacred most of the citizens of Morrow, we would expect them to seek revenge. That would be natural, understandable, even acceptable. But what about a people that, when you slaughter
 hundreds of them, doesn\rquote t even really notice? That don\rquote t acknowledge the event? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid10122328\charrsid6828570 We can\rquote t acce}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid685086\charrsid6828570 p}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid10122328\charrsid6828570 t that reaction}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 . That would be incomprehensible. So we tack the idea of \lquote revenge\rquote 
 onto the Silence so we can sleep better at night\emdash because we think, we actually h
ave the nerve to think, that we understand these creatures that live beneath us. And if we think we understand them, if we believe they are like us in their motivations, why, then we don\rquote 
t fear them quite as much. If we meet one in a dark alley, we believe
 we can talk to it, reason with, communicate with it. Or if we see one dozing beneath a red flag on the street during the day, we overlook it, we make it part of the scenery, no less colorful or benign }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
