. All sorts of trees grew in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Stockton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, but the difference between the staid oaks that lined our street and the misshapen, twisted, coiled welter of tree limbs in the forest seemed profound. It both reassured us and menaced us in our youth: limitless adventure, fear of the unknown.
\par \tab Our house lay on the forest\rquote s edge. The trees stretched on for hundreds of miles, over hills and curving down through valleys. Various were the forest\rquote s names, from the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Western Forest{\*\xmlclose}
 to the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Forest{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Owls{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to Farely\rquote s {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Forest
{\*\xmlclose}, after the man who had first explored the area. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Stockton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 had been nestled comfortably on its eastern flank for centuries, feeding off of the timber, the sap, the animals that took shelter there. Even though {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Stockton{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} was marginally to the south of Ambergris}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid7684672\charrsid6828570 \emdash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 across the River Moth from it}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid7684672\charrsid6828570 \emdash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Stockton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 was much more temperate because of the forest. It never got as sweltering as Ambergris.
\par \tab By the time I had turned thirteen and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} was nine, we had made the forest our own. We had colonized our tiny corner of it\emdash 
cleared paths through it, made shelters from fallen branches, even started a tree house. Dad never enjoyed the outdoors, but sometimes we could persuade him to enter the forest to see our latest building project. Mom had a real fear of the forest\emdash 
of any dark place, which may have come from growing up in Ambergris. (I never had the sense that growing up in Ambergris had been a trauma for her\emdash she lived there during very calm times\emdash but it is true she never talked about it.)
\par \tab One day, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} decided we should be more ambitious. We had made a crude map of what we knew of the forest, and the great expanse labeled \'93
Unknown\'94 irked him. The forest was one thing that could genuinely be thought of as his, the one area where he did not mimic me, where I followed his lead.
\par \tab We stood at the end of our most ambitious path. It petered out into bushes and pine needles and the thick trunks of trees, the bark scaly and dark. I breathed in the {\*\atrfstart 108182087}fresh-stale }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
