\par \tab \'93How }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 much}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570  farther?\'94 I asked.
\par \tab I had become increasingly aware that our parents counted on me to keep watch over {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Ever since he\rquote 
d gotten trapped in a tunnel the year before, we\rquote d all become more conscious of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}\rquote s reckless curiosity.
\par \tab \'93I don\rquote t know,\'94 he said. \'93If I did, it wouldn\rquote t be much of an adventure. But there\rquote s something out there, something we need to find.\'94
\par \tab His expression was mischievous, yes, but also, somehow, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 otherworldly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 
. (Otherworldly? I was nine. There was nothing \'93otherworldly\'94 about me. I liked to belch at the dinner table. I liked to blow bubbles and play with metal soldiers and read books about pirates and talking bears.)
\par \tab \'93But there\rquote s all that bramble,\'94 I said. \'93It will take ages to clear it.\'94
\par \tab \'93No,\'94 he said, with a sudden sternness I found endearing, and a little ridiculous, coming from such a gangly frame. \'93No. We need to go out exploring. No more paths. We don\rquote t need paths.\'94
\par \tab \'93Well...,\'94 I said, about to give {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} my next objection.
\par \tab But he was already off, tramping through the bramble like some miniature 
version of the Kalif, determined to claim everything he saw for the Empire. He had always been fast, the kind to set out obstinately for whatever goal beckoned, whatever bright and shiny thing caught his eye. Usually, I had control over him. Usually, he w
anted to stay on my good side. But when it came to the forest, our relationship always changed, and he led the way.
\par \tab So off he dashed into the forest, and I followed, of course. What choice did I have? Not that I hated following him. Sometimes, because of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, I was able to do things I wouldn\rquote t have done otherwise. And, such a relief, when I followed him, the weight of being the eldest lifted from me\emdash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid12067414\charrsid6828570 that was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 a rare thing, even BDD. 
\par \tab The forest in that place had a gathered a concentrated darkness to it because of the thick underbrush and the way the leaves and needles of the trees diluted the sun\rquote 
s impact. To find a patch of golden sunlight in the gloom was like finding gold, but }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\cf0\revised\revauth1\revdttm110566623\insrsid11351199\charrsid6828570 those patches }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 only accentuated the surrounding darkness}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \deleted\f39\revauthdel1\revdttmdel110566623\insrsid9058111\delrsid11351199\charrsid6828570  all the more}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 . The smell of rot caused by shadow was a healthy smell\emdash I didn\rquote 
t mind it; it meant that all of the forest still worked to fulfill its cycle, even down to the smallest insect tunneling through dead wood. It did not mean what it would come to mean in Ambergris.
\par \tab Dun
can and I fought our way through and over stickery vines and close-clumped bushes. We felt our way over fallen trees, stopping in places to investigate nests of flame-colored salamanders and stipplings of rust-red mushrooms. The forest fit us snugly; we w
e
re neither claustrophobic nor free of its influence. The calls of birds grew strange, shrill, and then died away altogether. (As if we had gone through a door to a different place, a different time, Janice. I could not believe, sometimes, while in the for
est, that it existed in the same world as our house.)
\par \tab At times, the ground rose to an incline and we would be trudging, legs lifting for the next step with a grinding effort. The few clearings became less frequent, and then for a long time we walked throug
h a dusk of dark-green vegetation under a canopy of trees like black marble columns, illuminated only by the stuttering glimmer of a firefly, or even just the repetitive clicking of some insect. A smell like ashes mixed with hay surrounded us. We had both
 begun to sweat, despite the coolness of the season, and I could hear even undaunted {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} breathing heavily. We had come a long way, and I wasn
\rquote t sure I could find the route back to our familiar paths. Yet something about this quest, this foolhardy plunge
 forward, became hypnotic. A part of me could have kept on going hour after hour, with no end in sight, and been satisfied with that uncertainty. (Then you know how I have felt my entire adult life\emdash except}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid12067414\charrsid6828570  that}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570  we\rquote re told there is no uncertainty. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 No one makes it out}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 , we\rquote re told, from birth until our deathbed, in a thousand spoken and unspoken ways.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid15732085\charrsid6828570 
 It is just a matter of when and where\emdash and if I could discover the truth in the meantime.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 )
\par \tab The sting, the burn, of hard exercise, the doubled excitement and fear of the unknown, kept me going for a long time.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid10711699\charrsid6828570  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 But, finally, I reached a point where fear overcame excitement. (You mean common sense overcame excitement.)
\par \tab \'93{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}!\'94 I said finally, to his back. \'93We have to stop. We need to find our way home.\'94
\par \tab He turned then, his hand on a tree trunk for support\emdash a shadow framed by a greater gloom\emdash and I\rquote ll never forget what he said. He said, \'93There is no way to go but forward, Janice. If we go forward, we will find our way back.\'94

\par \tab It sounded like something Dad would have said, not a nine-year-old kid.
\par \tab \'93We\rquote re already lost, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. We have to go back.\'94
\par \tab {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} shook his head. \'93I\rquote m not lost. I know where we are. We\rquote re not }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 there}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570  yet. I know something important lies ahead of us. I know it.\'94
\par \tab \'93{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose},\'94 I said, \'93you\rquote re wearing }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 sandals}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 . Your feet must be pretty badly cut up by now.\'94
\par \tab \'93No,\'94 he said, \'93I\rquote m fine.\'94 (I wasn\rquote t fine. The bramble}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid12067414\charrsid6828570 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570  had lacerated my feet, but I
\rquote d decided to block out that discomfort because it was unimportant.)
\par \tab \'93There\rquote s something ahead of us,\'94 he repeated.
\par \tab \'93Yes, more forest,\'94 I said. \'93It goes on for hundreds of miles.\'94 I thought about whether I had the strength to carry a kicking, struggling {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} all the way back to the house. Probably not.
\par \tab I looked up, the long trunks of trees reaching toward a kaleidosc
ope of wheeling, dimly light-spackled upper branches, amid a welter of leaves. In those few places where the light was right, I could see, floating, spore and dust and strands of cobweb. Even the air between the trees was thick with the decay of life, 
{\*\atrfstart 108182819}and as I type these words I wonder now if the underground is anything like deep forest}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs24\v\insrsid5181854\charrsid6828570 {\*\atrfend 108182819}{\*\atnid LG}{\*\atnauthor Liz Gorinsky}\chatn 
