\par \tab Another half-hour or so\emdash just as I could no longer identify our direction, so too I had begun to lose my sense of time\emdash and a thick, suffocating panic had begun to overcome me. We were lost}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\insrsid15732085\charrsid6828570 .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \deleted\f39\revauthdel1\revdttmdel110566633\insrsid9058111\delrsid5181854\charrsid6828570  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \deleted\f39\revauthdel1\revdttmdel110566633\insrsid10711699\delrsid5181854\charrsid6828570  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 We
 would never make it home. (You should have trusted me. You will need to trust me.)
\par \tab But {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 kept walking forward, into the unknown, through bramble and brush, over half-rotted tree branches, the thick loam of the forest floor rising at times to his ankles.
\par \tab Then, to my relief, the undergrowth thinned, the trees became larger but spread farther apart. Soon, we could walk unimpeded, over a velvety compost of earth covered with moist leaves and pine needles. A smell arose from the ground, a rich smell, alm
ost like coffee or muted mint. I heard again the hawk that had been wheeling overhead earlier, and an owl in the murk above us.
\par \tab {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} stopped for me then. He must have known how tired and thirsty I was, because he took my hand in his, and smiled as he said, \'93
I think we are almost there. I think we almost are.\'94
\par \tab We had reached the heart\emdash or a heart\emdash of the forest, I think. We had reached a place that in a storm would be called the eye. The light that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid15732085\charrsid6828570 shone }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 through from above did so in shafts as thin as the g
reen fractures of light I can see from the corner of my eye as I type up this account. And in those shafts, the dust motes floated yet remained perfectly still. Now I heard no sound but the pad of our feet against the loamy earth.
\par \tab {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} stopped. I was so used to hurrying to keep up that I almost bumped into him.
\par \tab \'93There,\'94 he said, pointing, a smile creasing his face.
\par \tab And I gasped, for there, just ahead of us, stood a statue.
\par \tab Made of solid gray stone, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid15732085\charrsid6828570 fissured,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570  splashed with light, overgrown with an emerald-and-crimson lichen, }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid15890644\charrsid6828570 the idol had}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 
 a face with large, wide eyes, a tiny nose, and a solemn mouth. The statue could not have been taller than three or four feet.
\par \tab We walked closer, in an effortless glide, so enraptured by this vision that we forg}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid15890644\charrsid6828570 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 t the ache in our legs.
\par \tab Iridescent beetles had woven themselves into the lichen beads of its smile, some flying around the object, effortless on tiny wings, heavy bodies drooping below the wings. Other insects had hidden in the fissures of the stone. What looked like a wren
\rquote s nest decorated part of the top of the head. A whole miniature world had grown up around it. It was clearly the work of one of the native tribes that had fled into the interior when our ancestors had built {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Stockton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and claimed the land around it. This much I knew from school.
\par \tab \'93How?\'94 I asked in amazement. \'93How did you know this was here, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?\'94
\par \tab {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Duncan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} smiled as he turned to me. \'93I didn\rquote t. I just knew there had to be something, and if we kept looking long enough, we\rquote 
d find it.\'94
\par \tab At the time, 
