Two days before I left that place for a succession of other places, Edward told me he loved me as we played another ludicrous game of lawn bowling in the tiny interior courtyard around which the building curled like a half-open fist\emdash 
me unable to hold the ball because of my traitorous wrist, him short-sighted and uncoordinated. Our legendar
y games lasted for brutal hours of incompetence while Martha, Daniel, the unnamed writer, and Sandra watched with a kind of disinterested interest. This was the first time Edward had used recognizable human speech.
\par Applying the doctor\rquote s advice like a universal salve for any ill, I told Edward the truth: at the moment, I had no capacity for any kind of love. I did not love him back. I didn\rquote t love anyone back. I wouldn\rquote 
t have loved myself back if I\rquote d walked past myself on a deserted street\'85
\par The day before I left, Edward used a variation on the Janice Shriek Method to try to kill himself. He stood in his corner as usual, his hands hidden as he cut at his wrists with a piece of metal he\rquote 
d loosened from the underside of one of the deck chairs. He slowly rubbed the skin and flesh off of his wrists until the blood came and his body trembled with the anticipation of stillness.
\par He stood there for at least an hour, propped up by the wall, the blood hidden by his gray robes. He must have been very determined. I imagine the blood sang softly to him, comforting him. So I imagine. The truth must have a harder, sharper edge.}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid5860459\charrsid6828570  I}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid9058111\charrsid6828570 t }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\insrsid5860459\charrsid6828570 certainly }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
